Basic Linux Commands 
pwd: tells where we are: file under file under file 
-- just type it out 

cd: which one of the folders you want to go to, change directory 
--type cd and then which folder you want to head into 
--cd .. goes back one step 

ls: lists all the files under the folder in which you are in
-- just type it out 

mv: renames the file 
-- type mv and then the name of the that is renamed and then the new name 
-- ex.) mv nameOfFile newName 

cp: makes a copy of the file
-- call cp then the name of the one that a copy is made of then the name of the new file
--ex.) cp orginalFile newFileName

touch: creates a new file 
--call touch and then the name of the new file 
--ex.) touch newFile

rm: removes a file 
-- call rm and also just the file name 
--ex.) rm deleteFile

head, tail, cat: opens the file 
head prints the first 10 lines, tail does the last 10 lines and cat opens the whole thing
--call head/tail/cat and then the file name that is being opened 
--ex.) head/tail/cat fileName 
**Note: add .py to the end of the name to create a file where code can be written 

man: using this explains what a command does, kind of like a docs tab;
however, it can be a little hard to understand
--call man and then the command name 
--ex.) man commandName(any of the above), to go back press q

python3 fileName: executes and runs the code
